1️⃣ Isolation Levels
First Problem: Why do we need isolation?

Imagine two ATMs updating the same bank account at once.

Balance = ₹5000

ATM A withdraws ₹1000
ATM B withdraws ₹2000

If both read old balance at same time:

Both see 5000

A writes 4000
B writes 3000

Final becomes wrong ❌

Should have been ₹2000.

Isolation prevents this.
Mental Model 🧠
Isolation = Transactions should not interfere
Common Problems
Dirty Read

👉 Reading data another transaction has not committed yet.

Example:

Transaction A changes salary to 50,000 but hasn't committed.

Transaction B reads it.

Then A rolls back.

B read fake data ❌

Non-Repeatable Read

Same query gives different answers inside same transaction.

Read 1 → salary 50000
Another transaction updates salary
Read 2 → salary 55000

Confusing.

Phantom Read

Rows appear/disappear between reads.

Isolation Levels (Interview Favorite)
🔹 Read Uncommitted

Fastest
Least safe

Allows dirty reads.

🔹 Read Committed

Prevents dirty reads.

Common default.

🔹 Repeatable Read

Prevents non-repeatable reads.

🔹 Serializable

Highest safety.

Acts almost like transactions run one by one.

Slow but safest.

Easy Memory Trick
Safety increases downward:

Read Uncommitted
Read Committed
Repeatable Read
Serializable

Higher safety → less concurrency.

Python Analogy 🧠

Think of file locking:

lock.acquire()
update_balance()
lock.release()

Isolation is similar idea.

2️⃣ Deadlocks
Simple Idea

A deadlock happens when two transactions wait on each other forever.

Mental Model 🧠

Two friends blocking each other in a narrow hallway.

Nobody moves.

Example

Transaction A locks Table1 and wants Table2.

Transaction B locks Table2 and wants Table1.

A waits for B
B waits for A

Stuck forever

Deadlock ❌

Visual
A holds Resource1 → wants Resource2

B holds Resource2 → wants Resource1

Cycle formed.

Why It Happens

Usually because:

Different lock order
Long transactions
Too much contention
How DB Solves It

Databases detect deadlocks and kill one transaction.

Victim transaction rolls back.

Preventing Deadlocks

✔ Access resources in same order
✔ Keep transactions short
✔ Avoid unnecessary locks

Python Analogy
Thread1 locks A then B
Thread2 locks B then A

Classic deadlock.

Memory Trick 🧠
Deadlock = Circular waiting
🔥 Placement Insight

Very common questions:

Q1: What is deadlock?

👉 Circular waiting between transactions.

Q2: Highest isolation level?

👉 Serializable

Q3: Difference between concurrency and isolation?

Concurrency → many users work together
Isolation → they don't corrupt each other

